        <section class="section sec4 " id="blogs">
            <div class="blogs-content">
                <div class="main-title">
                    <h2>My  <span>Blogs</span> <span class="bg-text">My Blogs</span> </h2>
                </div>
                <div class="blogs">

                    <div class="blog">
                        <img src="img/blog1.jpg" alt="">
                        <div class="blog-text">
                            <h4>
                                Static website deployment to AWS - and add CI/CD
                            </h4>

                            <div class="left-about">
                                <ol>
                                    <li><strong>Creating a Personal Resume Website</strong>
                                        <p>Building a personal resume website like <a href="https://urigakuru.uriroots.com" target="_blank">urigakuru.uriroots.com</a> involves a combination of front-end development, cloud services, and automation tools.</p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li><strong>Front-End Development</strong>
                                        <ol>
                                            <li>Use <strong>HTML, CSS, and JavaScript</strong> to structure the content, style the presentation, and add interactivity to the website.</li>
                                        </ol>
                                    </li>
                                    <li><strong>Hosting and Deployment</strong>
                                        <ol>
                                            <li><strong>Amazon S3:</strong> Host the website as a static site on Amazon S3, which provides scalable storage and high availability.</li>
                                            <li><strong>Amazon CloudFront and AWS Certificate Manager:</strong> Use CloudFront, a content delivery network (CDN), with AWS Certificate Manager to distribute the website globally, ensuring low latency and HTTPS security.</li>
                                            <li><strong>Amazon Route 53:</strong> Manage the domain name with Route 53, directing traffic to the S3-hosted website.</li>
                                        </ol>
                                    </li>
                                    <li><strong>Optional Backend Services</strong>
                                        <ol>
                                            <li><strong>Amazon DynamoDB:</strong> Use this NoSQL database service to store data like page views or visitor information, enabling dynamic content updates and analytics tracking.</li>
                                            <li><strong>Amazon API Gateway and AWS Lambda:</strong> Create APIs that interact with DynamoDB for dynamic functionalities without managing servers.</li>
                                        </ol>
                                    </li>
                                    <li><strong>Infrastructure as Code (IaC)</strong>
                                        <ol>
                                            <li><strong>Terraform:</strong> Automate infrastructure deployment using Terraform for consistent and repeatable setups.</li>
                                        </ol>
                                    </li>
                                    <li><strong>Continuous Integration and Continuous Deployment (CI/CD)</strong>
                                        <ol>
                                            <li><strong>GitHub and GitHub Actions:</strong> Manage source code with GitHub and use GitHub Actions to facilitate automated testing and deployment.</li>
                                        </ol>
                                    </li>
                                    <li><strong>Automation and Scripting</strong>
                                        <ol>
                                            <li><strong>Python, HCL, YAML, JSON, and Linux:</strong> Leverage these scripting languages and tools for automation, configuration, and deployment tasks.</li>
                                        </ol>
                                    </li>
                                </ol>
                            </div>
                            
                            <!-- <ul>
                                <li>**Creating a personal resume website like urigakuru.uriroots.com involves a combination of front-end development, cloud services, and automation tools.**</li>
                                <li>**Front-End Development:**
                                  <ul>
                                    <li>HTML, CSS, and JavaScript: These core web technologies are used to structure the content, style the presentation, and add interactivity to the website.</li>
                                  </ul>
                                </li>
                                <li>**Hosting and Deployment:**
                                  <ul>
                                    <li>Amazon S3: The website is hosted as a static site on Amazon S3, which offers scalable storage and high availability.</li>
                                    <li>Amazon CloudFront and AWS Certificate Manager: CloudFront, a content delivery network (CDN), is used alongside AWS Certificate Manager to distribute the website globally with low latency and secure it with HTTPS.</li>
                                    <li>Amazon Route 53: This DNS web service manages the domain name, directing traffic to the website hosted on S3.</li>
                                  </ul>
                                </li>
                                <li>**Backend Services (Optional):**
                                  <ul>
                                    <li>Amazon DynamoDB: A NoSQL database service like DynamoDB can be used to store data such as page views or visitor information. This allows for dynamic content updates and analytics tracking.</li>
                                    <li>Amazon API Gateway and AWS Lambda: These services can be used to create APIs that interact with DynamoDB, enabling dynamic functionalities without managing servers.</li>
                                  </ul>
                                </li>
                                <li>**Infrastructure as Code (IaC):**
                                  <li>Terraform: Infrastructure deployment is automated using Terraform, allowing for consistent and repeatable setups.</li>
                                </li>
                                <li>**Continuous Integration and Continuous Deployment (CI/CD):**
                                  <ul>
                                    <li>GitHub and GitHub Actions: Source code is managed in GitHub, with GitHub Actions facilitating automated testing and deployment.</li>
                                  </ul>
                                </li>
                                <li>**Automation and Scripting:**
                                  <ul>
                                    <li>Python, HCL, YAML, JSON, Linux: Various scripting languages and tools are utilized for automation, configuration, and deployment tasks.</li>
                                  </ul>
                                </li>
